OREON Jaw Crusher Maintenance Manual

The primary jaw crusher reduces run-of-mine ore between a fixed jaw and a moving jaw driven by an eccentric shaft and flywheel. Health indicators include toggle plate wear, manganese jaw-liner wear, eccentric bearing temperature rise, flywheel vibration, drive-belt slip, and abnormal crushing noise or ring bounce.

Common failure modes: jaw-plate wear and uneven gap cause oversize product and reduced throughput; toggle-plate fatigue or breakage from tramp metal or uncrushable material; eccentric-shaft bearing overheating from lubrication starvation or seal failure; flywheel imbalance from broken counterweights; and drive-belt glazing or misalignment producing slip and capacity loss.

Corrective actions: measure the closed-side setting and reset shims when product size drifts; replace manganese jaw liners in pairs when worn beyond forty percent; inspect and replace the toggle plate after any tramp-metal event; grease eccentric bearings on schedule and verify oil flow and temperature; re-tension or replace the V-belts and laser-align the drive; and always clear the crushing chamber before a restart.

Lubrication: use EP-2 grease on the eccentric bearings and verify central lubrication pump pressure and timer operation. A bearing temperature above eighty degrees Celsius indicates lubrication starvation or seal ingress and must be investigated before continued operation.
